\par The plaintiff contends that it does.  The defendant denies it.
\par 
\par }{\i\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 Representations:
\par }{\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 Mr. Wabwire Anthony for the plaintiff.
\par Mr. Moses Kazibwe for the defendant.
\par 
\par The phrase \lquote Cause of action\rquote  is defined by Osborn\rquote s Concise Law Dictionary, 9}{\super\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 th}{\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657  Edn, p. 73 as:
\par }\pard \qj \li1122\ri1595\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin1595\lin1122\itap0\pararsid10442657 {\b\i\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 \'93The fact or combination of facts which gives rise to a right of action.\'94
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10442657 {\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 
\par Halsbury\rquote s Laws of England, 4}{\super\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 th}{\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657  Edn (Re-issue), vol. 37 at p. 24 explains it thus:
\par }\pard \qj \li1122\ri1034\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin1034\lin1122\itap0\pararsid10442657 {\b\i\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 \'93Cause of action.  \lquote Cause of action\rquote 
 has been defined as meaning simply a factual situation the existence of which entitles one person to obtain from the Court a remedy against another person.  The phrase has been held from the earliest time to include every f
act which is material to be proved to entitle the claimant to succeed, and every fact which the defendant would have a right to traverse.  \lquote Cause of action\rquote 
 has also been taken to mean the particular act on the part of the defendant which gives the claimant his cause of complaint, or the subject matter or grievance founding the claim, not merely the technical cause of action.\'94
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10442657 {\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 
\par It is such an important aspect of our law that 0.6 r. 1 (a) requires all pleadings, generally, to contain a brief statement of the 
material facts on which the party pleading relies for claim or defence.  Under 0.7 r. 1 (e), the plaint must contain the facts constituting the cause of action and when it arose.  The consequences of non-compliance are }{\insrsid2185127\charrsid10442657 
grave}{\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 .  They are set out in 0.7 r. 11.  Under 0.7 r. 11 (a), a plaint that discloses no cause of action must be rejected by the Court.
\par 
\par It is, in my view, settled law that the question whether or not a plaint discloses a cause of action must be determined upon perusal of the plaint alone, together with anything attached as to form part of it.  
\par See:  }{\b\ul\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 Jeraj Shariff & Co. \endash Vs- C}{\b\ul\insrsid2185127\charrsid10442657 hotai}{\b\ul\insrsid4540011\charrsid10442657  Fancy Stores [1960] EA 374 at 375.}{\insrsid14500961\charrsid10442657 
\par }{\insrsid4540011\charrsid10442657 
\par I have studied the plaint.  In para 4 thereof, the plaintiff states that sometime in early 2000, the plaintiff through its Managing Director one Costa Bwambale}{\insrsid2185127\charrsid10442657 ,}{\insrsid4540011\charrsid10442657 
 entered into a dealership agreement with M/S Caltex (U) Ltd wherein the latter would supply lubricants to Caltex Rwenzori Service Station under the plaintiff\rquote s management.  The plaintiff states further that the dealer suppl
ied the plaintiff with lubricants for the period March 2000 until June 2005 for which the plaintiff duly paid Value Added Tax.  The invoices for the said period are attached.  There is no mention of Star Station Kasese in the plaint.
\par }{\insrsid6705150\charrsid10442657 
\par In }{\b\ul\insrsid6705150\charrsid10442657 Auto Garage & Others \endash Vs- Motokov (No. 3) [1971] EA 514, }{\insrsid6705150\charrsid10442657 
Spry, V.P. summarized the test to be applied in determining whether or not a plaint has disclosed a cause of action.  He said:
\par }\pard \qj \li935\ri847\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin847\lin935\itap0\pararsid10442657 {\b\i\insrsid6705150\charrsid10442657 \'93I would summarise the position as I see it by saying that if a plaint shows that the plai
ntiff enjoyed a right, that the right has been violated and the defendant is liable, then, in my opinion, a cause of action has been disclosed and any omission or defect may be put right by amendment.  If on the other hand, any of those essentials is miss
ing, no cause of action has been shown \'85\'85\'85\'85\'85.\'94
\par }\pard \qj \li0\ri0\sl360\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10442657 {\insrsid6705150\charrsid10442657 
\par Now the contents of para 4 of the plaint purport to show, in my opinion, that the plaintiff enjoyed a right.  And what was that right?  The right disclosed is, in my view, that of managing Caltex Rwenzori Serv
ice Station.  There is no evidence of this right being violated, let alone by the defendant.  The plaint states in para 4 (b) that the dealer supplied the plaintiff with lubricants for which}{\insrsid9577154\charrsid10442657 
 the plaintiff duly paid VAT.  This is where the problem lies. }{\insrsid6705150\charrsid10442657 
\par }{\insrsid9577154\charrsid10442657 
\par T
he defendant submits that the tax invoices submitted by the plaintiff were for recipients of taxable supplies who are not known to the defendant.  This is correct.  The invoices attached to the plaint which the plaintiff indeed relies on were issued to M/
S Caltex Rwenzori Service Station A/C Bwambale and M/S Star Station Kasese.  These are two distinct bodies, separate from the plaintiff, notwithstanding that the plaintiff was the one managing them.
\par 
\par The thrust of the defendant\rquote s submission is that the plai
ntiff and the two other companies are totally different and distinct persons and that Bwambale as an individual is a distinct person separate from the company.  I accept that argument.  It is sound and in line with settled law that a company is a distinct
 legal entity, separate from such persons as may be members of it, and having legal rights and duties and perpetual succession.  It may enter into contracts, own property, }{\insrsid32294\charrsid10442657 pay taxes, }{\insrsid9577154\charrsid10442657 
employ people and be liable for torts and crimes.  These are fundamental attributes long ago recognized in }{\b\ul\insrsid9577154\charrsid10442657 Salomon \endash Vs- Salomon & Co. Ltd [1897] A.C 22.
\par 
\par }{\insrsid9577154\charrsid10442657 The VAT law is clear that if, for any tax period, a taxable person\rquote s in put tax exceeds his/her liability for tax for that period, the excess tax is refundable:  S. 42 (1) of t
he Act.  The refund is subject to the Commissioner General being satisfied with the accounts/records submitted by the taxable person to substantiate his/her claim.
\par 
\par The Commissioner refused to make the refund because the documents the plaintiff submitted did not conform to the VAT Act and the Regulations.
\par 
\par I have considered the law as contained in the VAT Act, particularly S. 29 (1) thereof.  Under the said law, a taxable person making a taxable}{\insrsid11029877\charrsid10442657  supply has to provide the person receiving the supplies with a
 tax invoice.  It is very clear to me that the tax invoice is indeed the basic document evidencing the receipt of the taxable supply and on which a tax refund can validly be based.  In the instant case, the tax invoice was issued to companies very distinc
t
 from the plaintiff.  The plaintiff cannot take advantage of them.  The plaintiff is simply not sufficiently linked to those invoices to support its VAT refund claim.  Upon examination of the same, I do not find anything in them that would cause me to fau
lt the Commissioner General on the matter.  I would uphold the defence contention on this matter that the plaint discloses no cause of action against the defendant.}{\insrsid9577154\charrsid10442657 
\par }{\insrsid11029877\charrsid10442657 
\par Even if I were to take a rather generous view that taxes were indeed paid and ought to be refunded, it would appear to me that the plaintiff is remotely related to th}{\insrsid32294\charrsid10442657 ose invoices}{\insrsid11029877\charrsid10442657 
.  True, M/S Caltex Rwenzori Service Station and M/S Star Station Kasese are, within the meaning of S. 6 of the VAT Act taxable persons.  True also that they were being 
managed by the plaintiff through its Managing Director.  Under Sections 7 and 8 of the Act, they were obliged to register for VAT.  They did not for reasons best known to them.  They appear to be in clear breach of the law, deliberately or otherwise.}{
\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657   There is no evidence of any assignment of their tax obligations to the plaintiff to raise inference that the plaintiff has a sustainable claim against the defendant.  If }{\insrsid32294\charrsid10442657 
there was any assignment of rights}{\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657 , it is not pleaded in the plaint.  Even if Court were to clear the plaintiff to take advantage of invoices not in its names, the claim would in my view be }{
\b\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657 ex turpi causa}{\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657 .  In law an action does not arise from a base cause.  The policy was well summarized by Lord Mansfield C.J. in the 18}{\super\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657 th}{
\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657  Century when he declared: }{\insrsid11029877\charrsid10442657 
\par }{\i\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657 No Court will lend aid to a man who founds his cause of action upon an immoral or illegal act.  If the cause of action appears to arise }{\b\i\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657 ex turpi causa}{
\i\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657  \'85\'85\'85.. the Court says he has no right to be assisted: SUCCESS IN LAW by RICHARD BRUCE, 4}{\i\super\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657 TH}{\i\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657  EDN, p. 260}{
\insrsid11483425\charrsid10442657 .
\par }{\insrsid4748584\charrsid10442657 The }{\insrsid4726563\charrsid10442657 deliberate }{\insrsid4748584\charrsid10442657 non-compliance with the law would, in my view, render the claim base.
\par 
\par I would, therefore, agree with learned counsel for the defendant that allowing the tax invoices as submitted to benefit the plaintiff or even the two taxable companie
s would tantamount to sanctioning an illegality.  It is trite that a Court of law cannot sanction an illegality once brought to its attention.
\par 
\par In the result, I find that the plaint discloses no cause of action}{\insrsid3485609\charrsid10442657  against the defendant.  It is rejected in accordance with 0.7 r. 11 (a) of the Civil Procedure Rules.  The plaint is accordingly struck out.}{
\insrsid4748584\charrsid10442657 
\par }{\insrsid596853\charrsid10442657 
